 m.  ROADMAP: Technology Horizon to 2035 (From Theory to Solid-State Reality)

TEVS-R3 is a theoretical architectural framework. It is designed as a post-silicon roadmap targeting the physical and engineering capabilities of the mid-2030s. To prevent misinterpretation: **This architecture cannot be fabricated with commercial foundry processes today.** It relies on the convergence of three distinct technological horizons.

The table below delineates what is currently achievable in advanced physics laboratories versus the critical engineering thresholds that the community must solve over the next decade.

| Subsystem & Component | Current Lab State | Engineering Requirements for 2035 |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Optical Core Matrix**<br>*(Thin-Film Lithium Niobate on Sapphire)* | **Available.** High-quality TFLN wafers are commercially produced; 3-dB directional couplers and electro-optic modulators operate reliably above 40 GHz. | **Scale & Loss Reduction.** Integrating meters of S-shaped hollow-core channels on a single chip without prohibitive scattering losses ($< 0.1 \text{ dB/cm}$). |
| **Thermal Isolation**<br>*(1 µm Vacuum Gap between 30 K and < 2 K)* | **Theoretical Limit.** Macro-scale vacuum insulation is standard, but micro-scale separation fails due to Near-Field Radiative Heat Transfer (photon tunneling). | **Near-Field Suppression.** Development of photonic metamaterials and surface phonon-polariton filters to suppress radiative heat flux at the sub-micron scale. |
| **Structural Stability**<br>*(Active Metamaterial Scaffolding)* | **Experimental.** Piezoelectric nano-positioners exist but are bulky and rarely integrated directly into deep cryogenic CMOS/Photonics packages. | **Integrated Cryo-Metrology.** Monolithic integration of active, piezo-driven metamaterial frames that dynamically compensate for differential thermal contraction in real-time. |
| **Quantum Memory Matrix**<br>*(Rare-Earth Nuclear Spin)* | **Proven Principle.** Coherence times exceeding hours have been demonstrated in laboratories using isotopically purified crystals at milli-Kelvin temperatures. | **Multiplexed Interfacing.** Achieving high-fidelity evanescent coupling between the dynamic waveguide modes and the static nuclear spin states without causing thermal dephasing. |

### Architectural Status: Theoretical Framework

By framing TEVS-R3 as a target architecture, we avoid the physical bottlenecks of current planar silicon manufacturing. This document serves as a mathematical and geometric reference model. Each "Simulation Track" outlined in the repository is designed to isolate these specific engineering gaps and solve them through numerical physics simulations.
